Much more may this be said of Rome, with its great wealth, its large proletariat which had to be fed and amused at public eost, and its hordes of slaves who were sapping the very foundations of the empire by corrupting the home, the fountain of national strength. Nevertheless it seems likely that Juvenal, at least in those satires which are not purely general, had before his eye for the most part only the past, sometimes the distant past known to him only from history, but as a rule the reign of Domitian, during which his own early manhood was passed.
